summary: killing eve taking the time in 1x07 to show v reveling in her newfound freedom, taking in the prison guards murdered corpses,...
body:
killing eve taking the time in 1x07 to show v reveling in her newfound freedom, taking in the prison guards murdered corpses, juxtaposed next to someone like agniya who unknowingly chooses that same fate by refusing supposed emancipation is interesting as it brings up a couple of questions of what freedom truly means and represents in this world. perhaps it’s some sort of sign of what’s to come for v if she chooses to continue to be directed by the twelve. ultimately disposable.

v certainly appears to be completely liberated, riding off on a motorcycle with agniya’s body lying in the street quickly becoming nothing more than a blip. however we see the splinter between v’s perceived freedom vs. her actual freedom. finding out konstantin, the messenger and agent for v’s lifestyle, putting her in prison to try to save her from the twelve who ultimately provided for that very freedom only to turn it around and force hands for a v/konstantin confrontation in the name of self-preservation.

i love the strings starting to be yanked by the end of s1, rattling v’s controlled narrative. v doesn’t want to be completely autonomous — she wants to do her job very well after all — and parting ways would mean she would no longer have the $$$ or thrills. it does make me wonder if v would’ve ended up on the wrong side of the twelve’s graces at some point (regardless of her encounters with one former mi5 agent) with her continually flaunting and pushing their authority? but going back what’s really INCHteresting is that in her interactions with eve where she begins to start questioning others — and in doing so her own place in the scheme of things — which for v’s character is immensely huge. 

in 1x05 she tells eve they’re probably working for the same people and i can’t wait for that running theme of s2 and thusly how v and eve’s relationship will “progress and deepen” –sandra oh, god bless her. 

not to mention continue to push this internal dichotomy with v between a liberating existence within the confines of certain unknown prerequisites established by this Big Other vs. true autonomy that puts her and what she loves and knows — “nice life, cool flat, fun job” — in the crosshairs. how someone who prioritizes themselves above others and needing control of every situation will wrest with it all.

summary: Killing Eve is about a talented female assassin and the British intelligence officer trying to find her. The two are equally...
caption:
Killing Eve is about a talented female assassin and the British intelligence officer trying to find her. The two are equally obsessed with each other, and that is what sells the show. There’s a dangerous tension between the two. I can’t do it justice in this review, you’ve just got to watch.

This is a slick espionage show with brutal deaths. I typically watched this show before bed, and a few of Villanelle’s assassinations were still on my mind when I woke up in the morning. Despite the inherent gayness of the premise, this show (spoilers) still buries its most openly gay character. That trope continues to be upsetting and frankly mind-boggling. Kill off a straight for once. 

Despite that, I’m still kind of in love with this show and its characters. Shoutout to Sandra Oh’s curly hair.
